I'm certain I'll be hiring someone  Additional details Hi    We completed an extension and the builder encouraged us to do the hard landscaping. We have, in our haste and lack of planning made some errors. We do need to work with what we have though.   The key areas we would like to address this year are as follows:  Getting the water feature working better:  We set the waterfall as per the advice of the distributor but it blows around in the wind splashing everywhere and not at all relaxing.  Silencer needs to be bigger and fixed in to place. We understand this may be custom made.   Potential reducer on the pipe and filter maintenance.  The lining is loose so we need a contemporary solution to this looking better and securing the lights in place.   Behind the waterfall section we would like tall grass such as non evasive bamboo on pots to shield the fence, help diffuse some of the wind and create a soft sound.   At the back, we may look to take out the trees, level and put ground covering, potted acers etc. There is lighting and power throughout this area.   On the main patio we would like some shelter.   We like built in seating, free standing seating, custom built pergola's which would not require securing to the patio. We would concede and accept and umbrella if we had too.   We need the patio and render cleaned. I think acid with the patio and algae treatment on the render. This is the same at the front of the house.   We also would like a variety of potted plants around the lawn to add depth, texture, aroma, ambience and help with bio diversity.   We would like to have colour and texture all year round with some seasonal change.   We also appreciate that we have a bit of a wind tunnel down to the water feature so need to add in plants on the section leading on from the steps to help soften this.   Additional thoughts and advice would be appreciated.  Would be great to discuss and obtain quotes and timescales. Que/Ans: What kind of landscaping help are you looking for? Improve or refresh my current garden, Patio clean, algae off render, planting advice and implementation, water feature and maintenance. I'm certain I'll be hiring someone  Additional details Hi   I have been passed your details by Pauline Scoins.  We completed an extension and the builder encouraged us to do the hard landscaping. We have, in our haste and lack of planning made some errors. We do need to work with what we have though.   The key areas we would like to address this year are as follows:  Getting the water feature working well.  We set the waterfall as per the advice of the distributor but it blows around in the wind splashing everywhere and not at all relaxing.  Silencer needs to be bigger and fixed in to place.  Potential reducer on the pipe and filter maintenance. The lining is loose so we need a contemporary solution to this looking better and securing the lights in place.  Behind the waterfall section we would like tall grass such as non evasive bamboo on pots to shield the fence, help diffuse some of the wind and create a soft sound.  At the back, we may look to take out the trees, level and put ground covering, potted acers etc. There is lighting and power throughout this area.  On the main patio we would like some shelter. We like built in seating, free standing seating, custom built pergola's which would not require securing to the patio. We would concede and accept and umbrella if we had too.  We need the patio and render cleaned. I think acid with the patio and algae treatment on the render. This is the same at the front of the house.  We also would like a variety of potted plants around the lawn to add depth, texture, aroma, ambience and help with bio diversity.   We would like to have colour and texture all year round with some seasonal change.   We also appreciate that we have a bit of a wind tunnel down to the water feature so need to add in plants on the section leading on from the steps to help soften this. Additional thoughts and advice would be appreciated.  Additional Details: Hi   I have been passed your details by Pauline Scoins.
